# Generation 8: identity & self-reflection — answered from the self-model
# the agent wrote into its own KB at birth (derived from real state).
> who are you?
< I am parrot0.
> what are you?
< I am parrot0.
> do you exist?
< Yes, I am parrot0.
# gen51 (C1): capabilities described in PLAIN language, grounded in the real
# module set (a module absent from the KB contributes nothing) — not the
# module(...) jargon dump it used to be.
> what can you do?
< I can answer questions about facts and rules, do simple arithmetic, reason about cause and effect, compare quantities, tell whether two things are the same, remember things you tell me, read a short passage and pull out facts, track what a pronoun refers to, continue a sequence you teach me, remember what we talked about.
# gen64 (chat-sim driven): the capability intent is robust to chat-register
# shorthand. "u" -> "you" via canonicalization, so "what can u do?" reaches the
# same self-model answer instead of walling — the form many real users type.
> what can u do?
< I can answer questions about facts and rules, do simple arithmetic, reason about cause and effect, compare quantities, tell whether two things are the same, remember things you tell me, read a short passage and pull out facts, track what a pronoun refers to, continue a sequence you teach me, remember what we talked about.
# The reflexive payoff persists: the self-model is queried by the SAME logic
# engine as world knowledge — "who is a module?" resolves over module(X).
> who is a module?
< piact, compose, repair, input, deepreason, count, namestart, sequence, spell, world, translate, synth, induce, verify, memory, loop, meta, strategy, counterfactual, whatifnot, robust, calibrate, abduce, role, self, archetype, fewshot, compare, rulespec, algebra, arith, plan, wordproblem, agent, search, tool, quantity, cause, same, analogy, conj, gen, coref, bench, reader, shell, answerframe, knowledge, codeast, code, symbolic, summary, discourse, pragma, family, social, chitchat, reqgen, learn, smalltalk.
# gen145: self-challenge parity. parrot0 does not manage its own repo, but
# when the external loop poses a problem about parrot0 itself, it should propose
# a comparable smallest-change/test/journal solution instead of walling.
> review this implementation for your self-improvement loop: add a loop module, tests, version bump, and LOOP.md procedure.
< I would solve it by parity with the external loop: name the missing behavior, locate the owning module or registry point, add the smallest deterministic change, add English and Italian regression tests, bump my version, and journal the observed support quality. I can propose the change; an external agent still edits and verifies the files.
> solve this challenge about yourself: your fallback repeats when no module claims a turn
< I would treat it as a fallback gap: make the fallback or owning module handle that turn without pretending to understand, ratchet it with held-out English and Italian chats, bump my version, and record whether the wall got smaller. I can propose the change; an external agent still edits and verifies the files.

